    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "The sine is one of the fundamental functions of trigonometry (the\nmathematical study of triangles).  Consider a circle of radius 1\ncentered on the origin.  A ray comes in from the "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "+x"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " axis, makes\nan angle at the origin (measured counter-clockwise from that axis), and\ndeparts from the origin.  The "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "y"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " coordinate of the outgoing\nray's intersection with the unit circle is the sine of that angle.  It\nranges from -1 for "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "x=3\\pi / 2"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " to +1 for "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "\\pi / 2."
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "  The\nfunction has zeroes where the angle is a multiple of "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "\\pi"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ".\nSines of angles between "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "\\pi"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " and "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "2\\pi"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " are negative.\nThe numerous properties of the sine and related functions are included\nin any standard trigonometry text."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Notes"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
